{
  "card_id": "reversal_sequence",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Reversal Sequence",
  "aliases": [
    "order of reversal",
    "Order of Reversal",
    "purge-inversion-cisd sequence",
    "Purge-Inversion-CISD Sequence",
    "反转序列",
    "反转形成顺序",
    "完整反转模式"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A multi-step reversal confirmation pattern: begins with a liquidity sweep (Turtle Soup or SMT divergence), followed by inversion (closing through a fair value gap), then a change in state of delivery (close through opposing candles), and may culminate in a breaker block or new fair value gap, establishing a swing point for continuation entries.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify the initial purge: a Turtle Soup (price sweeps a prior swing high/low and closes back inside the range) or an SMT divergence between correlated assets.",
    "Confirm inversion: price trades back through the swept level and/or closes through the fair value gap generated by the sweep.",
    "Require a change in state of delivery: price must close through the series of opposing candles (down-close for bullish, up-close for bearish) that created the sweep, targeting a point of interest such as an order block, fair value gap, or opposing candle.",
    "Optionally, a new fair value gap or a breaker block pattern (e.g., low-high-lower low-higher high or vice versa) may form, providing further confirmation.",
    "Once the sequence is confirmed (purge + inversion + change in delivery), treat the swept extreme as the protected swing low/high — the invalidation point for framing continuation entries.",
    "Turtle Soup and SMT are alternative first steps; not both required.",
    "Breaker block requires a low-high-lower low-higher high (bullish) or high-low-higher high-lower low (bearish) structure."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "The sequence provides graded confirmation: early steps (Turtle Soup, inversion) offer better entry but lower certainty; later steps (change in delivery, breaker/FVG) increase confirmation with later entry. It confirms a directional shift, establishing an invalidation level at the swept swing point. Traders missing the initial reversal can wait for continuation setups—retracements into fair value gaps or sweeps of minor levels—for tighter stops. Focus on mastering one step for consistency.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Assuming the reversal entry was missed and abandoning the bias instead of looking for continuation entries.",
    "Chasing price after the initial reversal rather than waiting for a new order block, fair value gap retrace, or sweep to form.",
    "Treating a close as a continuation when price did not first sweep a low/high or reach into a fair value gap (unless paired with SMT on a correlated asset).",
    "Trying to catch the exact high or low instead of letting the structure form and trading the continuation.",
    "Attempting to identify every step in every reversal, leading to confusion; the sequence is not always complete.",
    "Dismissing a reversal because no SMT appears—SMT is an alternative to a purge, not a requirement.",
    "Entering prematurely without waiting for later confirmation, resulting in false signals.",
    "Confusing Breaker Block with Order Block (Breaker requires specific structure).",
    "Misplacing invalidation level at the original reversal low instead of the new swing point after CSD."
  ],
